paragraphs.text:
%md
# Load GS Data to HDFS
- Makes queries more efficient by storing the data directly into the HDFS
- Since the wdi_gs table points to a GS location, data must be transferred from GS to Hadoop cluster when running a query. It would be more efficient if the data is stored in the HDFS.SO,by moving data into the HDFS, the worker nodes are able to cache some of the data, allowing for subsequent queries to run faster.
- by comparing the processing time for `SELECT count(countryName) FROM` queries between loading from `wdi_gs` and `wdi_csv_text` we can see that the time takes for the GS location is 29s, however for data stored in hadoop, it only takes around 24s, as the worker nodes have cached some data to make it more efficient.

paragraphs.text: DROP TABLE IF EXISTS wdi_csv_text

CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE wdi_csv_text
(year INTEGER, countryName STRING, countryCode STRING, indicatorName STRING, indicatorCode STRING, indicatorValue FLOAT)
ROW FORMAT DELIMITED FIELDS TERMINATED BY ',' LINES TERMINATED BY '\n'
LOCATION 'hdfs:///user/swang/hive/wdi/wdi_csv_text'

INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE wdi_csv_text 
SELECT * FROM wdi_gs
SELECT count(countryName) as count FROM wdi_csv_text

paragraphs.text:
%md
# Hive vs. Bash
Peform the same command using Bash and Hive to compare the two.

Comparing the time it takes to run the `SELECT count(countryName) FROM wdi_csv_text` query above and the Bash script below, you can see that it takes about 36s for bash and 23s for using Hive. This is most likely due to the relatively small size of the data set. The Hive query has a lot of overhead like communication between master node and worker node, so the benefit of diving the work between the nodes isn't enough for a data set of this size to make much of a difference.

%sh
#SSH to master node
cd ~
hdfs  dfs -get  hdfs:///user/swang/hive/wdi/wdi_csv_text .
cd wdi_csv_text
#calculate current directory size
du -ch .
#1.8G	total

#clear fs cache
echo 3 | sudo tee /proc/sys/vm/drop_caches
#bash row count
date +%s && cat * | wc && date +%s

#40 seconds

paragraphs.text:
%md
# Parsing Issue
- Run the following query and discuss what could be wrong with the indicatorcode column.
by creating a debug table, we can clear see that the inappropriate parsing issue is caused by the delimiter character `,`.This was causing the default SerDe to split the rows up improperly, causing the incorrect indicator codes.
In order to fix this issue, a new gs table was created by using the OpenCSVSerd. Then exported the data to a hdfs location.

msg.data:
Parsing Issue

  • Run the following query and discuss what could be wrong with the indicatorcode column.
    by creating a debug table, we can clear see that the inappropriate parsing issue is caused by the delimiter character ,.This was causing the default SerDe to split the rows up improperly, causing the incorrect indicator codes.
    In order to fix this issue, a new gs table was created by using the OpenCSVSerd. Then exported the data to a hdfs location.

paragraphs.text:
SELECT distinct(indicatorcode)
FROM wdi_csv_text
ORDER BY indicatorcode
LIMIT 20

paragraphs.text: DROP TABLE IF EXISTS wdi_opencsv_gs

CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE wdi_opencsv_gs
(year INTEGER, countryName STRING, countryCode STRING, indicatorName STRING, indicatorCode STRING, indicatorValue FLOAT)
ROW FORMAT SERDE 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.serde2.OpenCSVSerde'
LOCATION 'gs://jarvis_data_eng_shawn/datasets/wdi_2016'
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS wdi_opencsv_text

CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE wdi_opencsv_text
(year INTEGER, countryName STRING, countryCode STRING, indicatorName STRING, indicatorCode STRING, indicatorValue FLOAT)
ROW FORMAT SERDE 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.serde2.OpenCSVSerde'
LOCATION 'hdfs:///user/swang/hive/wdi/wdi_opencsv_text'

INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE wdi_opencsv_text
SELECT * FROM wdi_opencsv_gs
SELECT count(countryName) as count FROM wdi_opencsv_text

paragraphs.text:
%md
# Compare execution time between `wdi_opencsv_text` and `wdi_csv_text` 
- for loading data from gs to hdfs it took about 26s however when using the `org.apache.hadoop.hive.serde2.OpenCSVSerde`, it took over 1minute. by looking into the `OpenCSVSerde` documentation, by using the `OpenCSVSerde`, it has limitation that SerDe treats all columns to be of type String where we can cast the value to different value type to make it work faster.

paragraphs.text:
%md
# 2015 Canada GDP Growth HQL
HQL queries to get the 2015 Canada GDP growth

The query to find the 2015 GDP growth for Canada is pretty simple, however, it takes a long time to execute. This is because the entire dataset must be search through to find the row with the correct values.As notcied in the following blocks, it takes a very long time(96s) to select the row(s). This is because it needs to iterate through the table to find the row that fits those criteria which is more than log(n) operation(as there will 3 iteration in total for indicator_code, year, and countryName).
To solve it, both partitioning and columnaring can be used and it is implemented in the following sections.

msg.data:
2015 Canada GDP Growth HQL

HQL queries to get the 2015 Canada GDP growth

The query to find the 2015 GDP growth for Canada is pretty simple, however, it takes a long time to execute. This is because the entire dataset must be search through to find the row with the correct values.

paragraphs.text:
select indicatorValue as gdp ,year,countryName
from wdi_opencsv_text
where indicatorcode = 'NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG'
and year = 2015
and countryName = 'Canada'

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Partition
- Use Hive partitions to speed up the Canada GDP growth query
by using partition the performance issue addressed in above section will be solved. The way partition works is that it will store data into different file based on the partition configuration. In the following block, a new table is created and it is partitioned by year. Therefore, the data is stored in a list of file distinguished by year. When a select query looking for rows identified by year is executed, the performance of the query will be increasedm,4s instead of 96s.

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Columnar File Optimization
- In this section, by storing data in a columnar format the performance issue got solved.
- In the following blocks, a table will be created as its data is stored as a parquet format. It is storing data grouped by column which means each column will be stored in the same lines. By doing this, the space it occupied is significantly decreased because it is using more compact encoding technique(2.3GB vs 137MB). Moreover, when doing a count query on a certain column, only data from that column will be processed. This will decrease I/O operations and hence increase the performance. 
Additionally, the parquet table is also faster at performing some queries. Compare the Canada 2015 GDP query below to the one on the wdi_opencsv_text table. The parquet one is much faster, as a columnar format allows the query to simply ignore any columns which are not needed.

paragraphs.text:
%md
# Highest GDP Growth
- Find the highest GDP growth (NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG) year for each country.

The first is ran using Hive, while the second is ran using Spark. Running the query with Spark took less time, as it performs its operations in main memory.

msg.data:
Highest GDP Growth

  • Find the highest GDP growth (NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG) year for each country.

The first is ran using Hive, while the second is ran using Spark. Running the query with Spark took less time, as it performs its operations in main memory.

paragraphs.text:
select Max(indicatorvalue) as gdp,countryname
    from  wdi_csv_text
    where indicatorcode = 'NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG' and indicatorvalue <>0

paragraphs.text:
select distinct a.countryname as country, b.indicatorvalue as GDP_growth_value,b.year as year 
from (
    select Max(indicatorvalue) as gdp,countryname
    from  wdi_csv_text
    where indicatorcode = 'NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG' and indicatorvalue <>0
    group by countryname
    ) a
    inner join wdi_csv_text b
    on a.countryname=b.countryname and b.indicatorvalue=a.gdp
